had done with the subject,

00:37:09.020 --> 00:37:11.400
and then tried everything.

00:37:11.400 --> 00:37:13.960
Persevering until he
could find something

00:37:13.960 --> 00:37:16.330
that would be uniquely his own.

00:37:16.330 --> 00:37:20.470
This image of a crumbled
hard cooked egg.

00:37:20.470 --> 00:37:25.740
Bob believed that besides
qualities of design, his activities

00:37:25.740 --> 00:37:29.260
on photography needed
to have purpose,

00:37:29.260 --> 00:37:33.030
and the purpose he found was
to fight for equal rights,

00:37:33.030 --> 00:37:36.140
support justice, and
help make change

00:37:36.140 --> 00:37:39.320
in peoples lives, for the better.

00:37:39.320 --> 00:37:42.270
He first got involved
with the Brooklyn Congress

00:37:42.270 --> 00:37:46.000
of Racial Equality, and became
their national photographer.

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:51.210
Brooklyn was where CORE
began the freedom rights.

00:37:51.210 --> 00:37:56.270
As you can see, people here --
they were picketing for education,

00:37:56.270 --> 00:38:01.000
as well as a livable community
and economic opportunity;

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:04.480
themes that Bob would
later expand upon.

00:38:04.480 --> 00:38:13.360
Through the civil rights movement,
Bob met many great people; Baldwin,

00:38:13.360 --> 00:38:17.690
the political thinker Michael
Harrington, but he was close --

00:38:17.690 --> 00:38:19.570
closeness he felt to Doctor

00:38:19.570 --> 00:38:22.770
and Reverend Martin
Luther King Junior was

00:38:22.770 --> 00:38:27.300
such that Bob always
referred to him as Doc.

00:38:27.300 --> 00:38:32.020
He attended King's funeral in
1968 and took intimate photographs

00:38:32.020 --> 00:38:34.920
of the family, which
have a permanent

00:38:34.920 --> 00:38:38.580
in the National King
Historic site in Atlanta.

00:38:41.430 --> 00:38:47.050
Bob's magazine work began in
the 1960s, often dove tailed

00:38:47.050 --> 00:38:51.310
with his civil rights photography,
which concerned voter drives

00:38:51.310 --> 00:38:55.360
in the south, as on the
left of the man registering

00:38:55.360 --> 00:38:58.210
in Sumter, South Carolina.

00:38:58.210 --> 00:39:02.000 position:56%
For Albany, he followed the Reverend
Joe Carter, the first black man

00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:06.490
to register and vote in West
of Louisiana, and in fact,

00:39:06.490 --> 00:39:11.590
I think he told you James that this
was the most dangerous situation he

00:39:11.590 --> 00:39:14.120
had ever faced.

00:39:16.150 --> 00:39:22.740
Bob was awarded a Guggenheim
foundation grant in 1964,

00:39:22.740 --> 00:39:27.290
and here are two examples of
that work; his proposal was

00:39:27.290 --> 00:39:30.730
to quote continuous work
on the efforts of Negroes

00:39:30.730 --> 00:39:35.510
to achieve equality in America,
and to begin the study of poverty

00:39:35.510 --> 00:39:38.930
in the context of contemporary
affluence.

00:39:38.930 --> 00:39:42.150
His application was supported
by Edward [inaudible],

00:39:42.150 --> 00:39:48.990
who loaded the valuable project,
and Bob as a serious thinker.

00:39:48.990 --> 00:39:54.020
His teacher, Brodovitch, pointed
to Bob's integrity and courage,

00:39:54.020 --> 00:39:58.020
and the vitality, and
necessity of the project.

00:39:58.020 --> 00:40:03.560
Dorothy Norman, [inaudible] future
biographer concurred, that Bob was,

00:40:03.560 --> 00:40:06.410
quote, "Dedicated and selfless,

00:40:06.410 --> 00:40:09.760
a person of integrity,
and shows promise.

00:40:09.760 --> 00:40:12.080
It's one of the most
effective photographers

00:40:12.080 --> 00:40:15.370
of the American social
scene" end quote.

00:40:15.370 --> 00:40:25.800 position:56%
On assignment, Bob was unafraid and
a charmer, with a gift for repartee.

00:40:25.800 --> 00:40:29.490
His editorial worked for
numerous magazines, included --

00:40:29.490 --> 00:40:31.580
we've already heard, Look, Live,

00:40:31.580 --> 00:40:35.320
New York Times magazine,
too many to say.

00:40:35.320 --> 00:40:39.640
The assignments were very
varied, and these are from a story

00:40:39.640 --> 00:40:43.130
about the daily life of
Sumter, South Carolina Sheriff,

00:40:43.130 --> 00:40:45.810
Jay [inaudible] Bornell [phonetic].

00:40:47.670 --> 00:40:55.490
Bob documented this drug raid
in New York, it was for Look.

00:40:55.490 --> 00:41:01.850 position:56%
He met and photographed many people,
such as Sidney Poitier, B.B King,

00:41:01.850 --> 00:41:04.450
Miles Davis, Tina Turner.

00:41:04.450 --> 00:41:10.830
One of the crowds he most
enjoyed hanging out with,

00:41:10.830 --> 00:41:16.670
were the pop artists;
James Rosenquist, Roy --

00:41:16.670 --> 00:41:18.530 position:56%
[inaudible], Andy Warhol and others.

00:41:18.530 --> 00:41:23.580
Being represented by art
gallery dealer Leo Costelli.

00:41:23.580 --> 00:41:26.650
For a magazine article,
Bob cleverly decided

00:41:26.650 --> 00:41:29.770
to take Andy Warhol
grocery shopping.

00:41:29.770 --> 00:41:39.160
[Inaudible] became a close
friend, Bob's love for art comes

00:41:39.160 --> 00:41:42.910
through here, in this portrait in
which the artist stays in position

00:41:42.910 --> 00:41:46.540
as the sculpture base,
bellow his own representation

00:41:46.540 --> 00:41:50.480
of Brancusi's 1910 Sleeping Views.

00:41:54.190 --> 00:41:59.030
Bob was a prolific producer
of more than 60 books,

00:41:59.030 --> 00:42:01.670
as well as many bookazines
[phonetic],

00:42:01.670 --> 00:42:05.920
continuing after he moved
from New York to Miami Beach.

00:42:05.920 --> 00:42:12.150
Some were his own, others were
with and for other people.

00:42:12.150 --> 00:42:14.970
This collage gives you
an idea of the range

00:42:14.970 --> 00:42:17.300
of these many book projects.

00:42:17.300 --> 00:42:23.920 position:56%
Some unusual, as in the lower right,
even body as [inaudible] of bibles

00:42:23.920 --> 00:42:25.530
on the lower right, the book

00:42:25.530 --> 00:42:31.030
about the right bold underground
comics, as a form of fog art.

00:42:31.030 --> 00:42:33.380
Bob, and the influential cartoonist

00:42:33.380 --> 00:42:37.300
and Editor Art Spiegelman
worked on it together.

00:42:37.300 --> 00:42:41.120
Next to that book cover, is this
project about the Bill of Rights,

00:42:41.120 --> 00:42:45.110
with the head of the American civil
liberty's union Aaron Glazer who's

00:42:45.110 --> 00:42:48.630
here today, called,
Visions of Liberty.

00:42:48.630 --> 00:42:52.510
Never far from Bob's mind
was concerned for equality,

00:42:52.510 --> 00:42:56.280
and education, and about
poverty, which eluded people

00:42:56.280 --> 00:42:58.630
from those American values.

00:42:58.630 --> 00:43:04.150
Here's an example of the
graphically art full lay out,

00:43:04.150 --> 00:43:07.650
that characterizes
Bob's book projects.

00:43:07.650 --> 00:43:11.920
An assignment looking at children
growing up without their fathers,

00:43:11.920 --> 00:43:17.800 position:56%
led in the 1970 to a serious of
small books for, and about children.

00:43:17.800 --> 00:43:20.650
Some elevating a play,
and many finding a way

00:43:20.650 --> 00:43:23.080
to improve reading skills.

