Down Home, photographed from
1956 to 1970 and published

00:43:31.300 --> 00:43:36.590
in 1971 was Bob's major
first book project,

00:43:36.590 --> 00:43:41.890
it is a sociologically study of
people living in Candem, Alabama.

00:43:41.890 --> 00:43:47.650
Bob continued photographing the
same people for over 30 years.

00:43:47.650 --> 00:43:50.840
He intended to publish Home again,

00:43:50.840 --> 00:43:54.170
but it became an unfinished
projects.

00:43:54.170 --> 00:43:59.830
Two of the young folks Bob met in
1956 are shown on the book pages

00:43:59.830 --> 00:44:04.360
on the left, and on the right
is how he found those two girls,

00:44:04.360 --> 00:44:06.750
ten years later.

00:44:06.750 --> 00:44:09.080
Bob was looking for
positive results,

00:44:09.080 --> 00:44:13.240
from the kind of civil right
actions he had participated in.

00:44:13.240 --> 00:44:18.260
In general, he was a
keen observer of process.

00:44:18.260 --> 00:44:21.750
There would be more of
this kind of photography.

00:44:23.990 --> 00:44:27.700
The better man of America
was Bob's focus.

00:44:27.700 --> 00:44:31.860
The next America, in 1974
was a project Bob did

00:44:31.860 --> 00:44:33.910
with Michael Herrington,
whom he had met

00:44:33.910 --> 00:44:36.260
through his earlier work with CORE.

00:44:36.260 --> 00:44:40.170
Harrington had written the other
America, which had had an impact

00:44:40.170 --> 00:44:44.640
on the Kennedy administration,
this time he and Bob would update

00:44:44.640 --> 00:44:49.180
that book with the decline
and rise of the United States.

00:44:49.180 --> 00:44:57.070
Bob was always showing America
how he saw it, and then attempting

00:44:57.070 --> 00:45:00.830
to do something about making
life in America better.

00:45:00.830 --> 00:45:05.350
He was putting his photographs
to use for social causes,

00:45:05.350 --> 00:45:10.110
how the other half still lived was
a petition to President Carter,

00:45:10.110 --> 00:45:14.240
to pay attention to the South
Bronx, done under the auspices

00:45:14.240 --> 00:45:16.810
of the Philps [inaudible]
Foundation.

00:45:16.810 --> 00:45:20.790
The library borrowed a rare
copy of these photographs,

00:45:20.790 --> 00:45:22.580
for its recent exhibition,

00:45:22.580 --> 00:45:24.650
highlighting the mock
breaking journalism

00:45:24.650 --> 00:45:26.310
of Jacob Breeze [phonetic].

00:45:26.310 --> 00:45:28.820
Brezze's [Inaudible] original how
the other half [inaudible] gave

00:45:28.820 --> 00:45:32.710
voice to the New York City
ten amends, of the 1880s.

00:45:32.710 --> 00:45:40.450
You can see that Bob was all
about America, here's a glance

00:45:40.450 --> 00:45:43.870
at the great American past time.

00:45:43.870 --> 00:45:45.690
Bob's study of the
Pittsburgh [inaudible],

00:45:45.690 --> 00:45:50.250 position:56%
as was during this season, following
the death of Roberto Clemente,

00:45:50.250 --> 00:45:54.530
who was killed in a
plane crash in 1972.

00:45:54.530 --> 00:45:56.820
It featured their all star player,

00:45:56.820 --> 00:46:01.790
and left fielder Willie
Stargell, during the 1973 season.

00:46:01.790 --> 00:46:06.120
As you can see, Bob got
into the game himself.

00:46:06.120 --> 00:46:14.390
Bob's own involvement in
things is most clearly seen

00:46:14.390 --> 00:46:19.670 position:56%
in the diet, which examined obesity.

00:46:19.670 --> 00:46:22.920
He produced photographs on
this subject for Esquire

00:46:22.920 --> 00:46:27.250
and for the London Sunday
Times on 1979 to 80.

00:46:27.250 --> 00:46:31.480
He took on, on an experimental
diet himself, he exercised,

00:46:31.480 --> 00:46:37.020
and under doctor's care
lost 100 pounds in a year.

00:46:37.020 --> 00:46:42.570
Bob relished the outcome, and
was never more proud of anything

00:46:42.570 --> 00:46:48.430
than this [inaudible] group of
photographs he made of himself.

00:46:48.430 --> 00:46:55.130
As you can see, Bob
liked to observe process.

00:46:55.130 --> 00:47:01.510
He followed how artist worked,
with close friend Roy Lichtenstein;

00:47:01.510 --> 00:47:07.430 position:56%
he was on set, as the artist applied
color, outline and dot matrixes

00:47:07.430 --> 00:47:12.030
for a mural size view,
of an iconic Oval office.

00:47:12.030 --> 00:47:14.330
Bob delighted in watching
the artist work.

00:47:14.330 --> 00:47:22.070
Carver County, produced in 1990
is a unique visual biography

00:47:22.070 --> 00:47:24.980
of the short story
writer Raymond Carver.

00:47:24.980 --> 00:47:27.820
Carver's letters and
poems provided the texts,

00:47:27.820 --> 00:47:32.050
and Bob's photographs helped
us match those gritty words,

00:47:32.050 --> 00:47:35.600
with images of the
bleak, blue colored towns

00:47:35.600 --> 00:47:38.770
of the author's native
Pacific North West.

00:47:38.770 --> 00:47:46.180
I'd say that Visions of
Liberty, from the early 1990s,

00:47:46.180 --> 00:47:48.800
summarizes what Bob stood for.

00:47:48.800 --> 00:47:52.140
And the body of photographs
he left us.

00:47:52.140 --> 00:47:56.840
Native American children in
the south west or women's march

00:47:56.840 --> 00:48:03.950
on New York City, a protestor
at an anti-Vietnam War rally,

00:48:03.950 --> 00:48:09.960
a family supporting gay rights.

00:48:09.960 --> 00:48:14.070
One of Bob's most popular
images, is this one,

00:48:14.070 --> 00:48:19.780
taken at the People's wall, at the
IBM at the world's fair in Queens

00:48:19.780 --> 00:48:24.840
in 1964, it is been
interpreted as a statement

